metadata.name: Staccato #102
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

Containing just three basic repeating shapes, 'Staccato' is inspired by minimalist geometric art.
Each 'Staccato' output forms a bold, colorful and (hopefully) pleasing design.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: Mines #106
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: reborn #196
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Elswhere #106
metadata.description:
Perlin noise walks into a Julia set and finds itself Elswhere. X is real, Y is imaginary, or is it the other way around? 

Elswhere is a unique generative art series in which noise and fractal math are combined to create whimsical shapes and motifs, with an infinite number of variations. Made with p5js.

For each pixel, the noise values corresponding to the X and Y coordinates are computed and then used as the real and imaginary components for initializing a Julia set recursion. The pixel is colored based on the number of steps it takes for the recursion to reach its base case.

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view.
[2] Render 2000x3000px image.
[4] Render 4000x6000px image.
[6] Render 6000x9000px image.

Created by Elsif, 2022.05

metadata.name: EDDY #256
metadata.description:
An eddy is a circular movement of water counter to a main current. It reminds me of innovations in art, like a small countercurrent to the mainstream, surfacing new techniques and aesthetics. 

I hope that EDDY will brighten your days with its playful swirl of colors, inspired by the sea, the sky, the birds, and post-impressionist paintings.

Keyboard Controls:
[F] Fill the window.
[S] Save the current view in live mode as an image (default 1125x1500px).
[1] [2] [4] [6] Change resolution, 1.5K to 9K.
[R] Reverse course.

Made with p5js and shaders.

Created by elsif, 2022.12.

metadata.name: De/FragV2 #367
metadata.description:
The second piece in this series is dedicated to another fundamental algorithm in computer graphics: Voronoi. It's origin precedes its use with computers by several decades, or centuries, depending on who to credit, since science always is a continuum. In the generative art & design field, the algorithm has been an instrumental tool for generation(s) of practioners, sadly often to the point of turning cliché.

In this piece I've attempted to "break" the classic resulting aesthetics of this algorithm and focus more on revealing its inner workings. There are many ways of computing a Voronoi diagram. The so called Jump Flood Algorithm (JFA) proved to be the visually most interesting approach to me. Again, as with the previous De/Frag piece, here the algorithm has been slowed down, timesliced and customized in dozens of ways to result in a more painterly character overall and produce a variety of new shapes & textures.

Fullscreen compatible (Press 'S' to toggle square frame). Made with love & thi.ng/umbrella

metadata.name: abstraction #24
metadata.description:
Diagrams of patterns on spheres, planets, fields, and platonic solids rendered isometrically. Ink on paper (on js).

Press DOWN to save an SVG suitable for plotting (or laser etching).
Press UP to save a 2400 x 2400 png. If you need a bigger image, zoom out and refresh, the canvas will fit the window.

Physics is fundamentally idealist. We search for simple rules from which the complexities of the universe emerge. But real systems are exceptionally complex, closed-form solutions are the exception. The deeper we dive into the fundamental nature of the universe, the less clear the rules become. Are the rules we've developed fundamental, or are they empirical approximations?

metadata.name: Sub Section Patina #901
metadata.description:
"Sub Section Patina" is inspired by street art and the marks and layering from that art form. If you zoom in on a small section of a wall that artists have marked, sprayed paint, and plastered with posters, some beautiful effects start to happen.

While the "Sub Section Patina" layers are building up, there is a tendency to destroy the layers below. The layering is similar to a wall many street artists have contributed. Sometimes just a section will be covered and filled with something else. Sometimes large areas of the canvas are covered up. Other layers will be put on top of one another, creating a new chaotic image. 

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
substack/point-in-polygon

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Pine Dream #121
metadata.description:
Pine dream by Asaf Slook (2022)

This work is an attempt to create a simple pen-like generated drawing, in a way that confuses the observer to perceive it to be a real unique hand-drawn piece.

Rare features:
- Lonely tree
- Static stroke
- Sunny day palette
- Dotted land
- Partial land
 
The best results are from 1000x1000 and above.

This work was created using p5.js and love :)
